// Explicit view: a type-alias name in a type position shows its backing type.
// A type-alias DECLARATION fills its elided ⟨type⟩ slot with the `type` meta — `base : type : int`:
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 11 8 1 1 type type"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 12 8 1 1 type type"
// The proc decl shows its (redundant) form type; each alias USE shows its backing:
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 13 8 1 1 type proc()()"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 14 11 1 0 alias (i32)"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 15 12 1 0 alias (i32)"
// Five SYN total: 2 alias-decl `type`, 1 proc form-type, 2 backing hints.
// RUN: test $(%build/arche-analyzer --dump %s 2>/dev/null | grep -c "^SYN ") -eq 5
base  :: int
level :: base
main  :: proc() {
  a : base  = 10;
  b : level = 20;
}
